## Guardrails (fill in)

<!-- Example sections — replace with your rules -->

### Scope

- (e.g. “No drive-by refactors outside the task.”)
- (e.g. “Match existing patterns in `apps/web` and `packages/mandate-engine`.”)

### Naming & branding

- Prefer **AgentCash** in user-facing copy and new docs.
- Internal package names (`@mandate/*`) may stay until a deliberate rename.

### Security

- Never commit `.env.local`, `Private.md` contents, or API keys into tracked files.
- Service role and Stripe keys only in env / dashboard.

### Reliability (Agent API — May 2026)

- **`/api/v1/*`** uses `runAgentRoute` (`apps/web/src/app/api/v1/_lib/run-agent-route.ts`): IP cap + per-agent tier limits (`src/lib/api/rate-limit.ts`) so a buggy agent or script cannot hammer **Stripe Issuing** / **Supabase** in a tight loop. Defaults are conservative; tune with `AGENT_API_*` env vars (see `apps/web/.env.local.example` and `docs/CLOUDFLARE.md`). Limits are **best-effort per Worker isolate** (reset on cold start), not a global DDoS product.
- **Errors**: `toErrorResponse` (`src/lib/api/http-errors.ts`) maps Stripe-like errors, PostgREST-like errors, JSON parse failures, and config errors to stable JSON without leaking raw vendor payloads. Policy violations stay **422** via `jsonFromEngine`.
- **Dashboard MCP key rotation**: `POST /api/agents/[id]/mcp-key` is capped per user per hour (`MCP_KEY_ROTATE_MAX_PER_HOUR`).
- When extending APIs, reuse **`runAgentRoute`** + **`toErrorResponse`** instead of ad-hoc `catch` messages.

### Deploy

- Cloudflare Worker name: **agentcash** (`apps/web/wrangler.jsonc`).
- Build: `npm ci && npm run build` or `npm run build:cf`; deploy: `cd apps/web && npx wrangler deploy`.

